er to work with in the real world.</p>                     <h2>Using ::class on objects</h2>                     <p>In the past, when you wanted to pass a class string to a method, you had to use something like <code>get_class</code>, which always felt a little pointless. The system already knows about the class at the time, as you have already autoloaded it in or created a new instance. Let's look at an example/</p>                     <pre><code data-theme="github-light" data-lang="php" class='torchlight' style='background-color: #fff; --theme-selection-background: #e2e5e9;'><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">1</span><span style="color: #6A737D;">// Before PHP 8.0</span></div><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">2</span><span style="color: #24292E;">$commandBus</span><span style="color: #D73A49;">-&gt;</span><span style="color: #6F42C1;">dispatch</span><span style="color: #24292E;">(</span><span style="color: #005CC5;">get_class</span><span style="color: #24292E;">($event), $payload);</span></div></code></pre>                     <pre><code data-theme="github-light" data-lang="php" class='torchlight' style='background-color: #fff; --theme-selection-background: #e2e5e9;'><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">1</span><span style="color: #6A737D;">// PHP 8.0</span></div><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">2</span><span style="color: #24292E;">$commandBus</span><span style="color: #D73A49;">-&gt;</span><span style="color: #6F42C1;">dispatch</span><span style="color: #24292E;">(</span></div><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">3</span><span style="color: #24292E;">    </span><span style="color: #6F42C1;">event</span><span style="color: #24292E;">: $event</span><span style="color: #D73A49;">::class</span><span style="color: #24292E;">,</span></div><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">4</span><span style="color: #24292E;">    </span><span style="color: #6F42C1;">payload</span><span style="color: #24292E;">: $payload,</span></div><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">5</span><span style="color: #24292E;">);</span></div></code></pre>                     <p>This might not be a show-stopper in terms of features, but it is definitely something I use and will always reach for when needed.</p>                     <h2>None capturing catch blocks</h2>                     <p>Sometimes when building an application, you don't need access to the exception that may be thrown. This is rarely the case for me, though. Your mileage may vary, though. Let's look at an example.</p>                     <pre><code data-theme="github-light" data-lang="php" class='torchlight' style='background-color: #fff; --theme-selection-background: #e2e5e9;'><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">1</span><span style="color: #6A737D;">// Before PHP 8.0</span></div><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">2</span><span style="color: #D73A49;">try</span><span style="color: #24292E;"> {</span></div><div class='line'><span style="color:#1b1f234d; text-align: right; -webkit-user-select: none; user-select: none;" class="line-number">3</span><span style="color: #24292E;">    $response </span><span style="color: #D73A49;">=</s